<HEADLINE>
14 ARTISTS SELECTED TO RESIDE IN OVERSEAS ARTISTIC VILLAGES
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March 15 (CNA) 03/15/07  21:36:00 (By Ruth Wang)
</P>
<P>
A total of 14 Taiwanese artists have been selected to reside in
six artist villages in the Czech Republic, France and America, a
spokesman of the Council for Cultural Affairs (CCA) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The artists -- of whom 11 are visual artists and three performing
artists -- were selected from 34 applicants to the CCA's
international artist-in-residence program which sends artists
abroad for cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Among the 11 visual artists, Huang Lan-ya and Chang Li-shan will
go to America's International Studio and Curatorial Program; Lin
Jen-shin and Chang Ying-ling will reside in Anderson Ranch Arts
Center, also in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chi-suei will be a resident artist in Egon Schiele Art
Centrum in the Czech Republic; Chen Sung-shih, Wu Tung-lung and
Yeh Yi-li will reside in Cite Internationale des Arts in France.
</P>
<P>
Of the remaining six yet-to-undecided candidates, two will be
resident artists at America's 18th Street Arts Complex, while the
third will reside at France's CAMAC.
</P>
<P>
The three performing artists: Su Wen-chi, Lee Tzu-sheng and Sun
Chuo-tai will reside in the Cite Internationale des Arts in
France, the spokesman said.
</P>
